The conventional chemical reduction method comprises of two steps—the reduction of Cr(VI) to Cr(III) by a reducing agent, at an acidic pH, and the precipitation of Cr(III) as an insoluble hydroxide at an alkaline pH. The chemical reductant can be any sulphur-based or iron-based salt. These two steps can be combined into a single step by the electrochemical addition of ferrous ion, rather than the addition of a ferrous salt (FeSO4 or FeCl2) which necessitates the use of an acidic and an alkaline pH, making it a two-step process. The removal of Cr(VI) by the former can be illustrated using the following reaction [70]:CrO4-2+8H++3Fe+2→Cr+3+3Fe+3+4H2O\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
